cff-version: 1.2.0
message: "If you use PRISM in your research or work, please cite it as below."
title: "PRISM: A Framework for LLM Research and Audits"
abstract: >-
  PRISM is a methodology for keeping multi-prompt, multi-session LLM research
  and audit work coherent across prompts, sessions, and the context limits of
  any single chat. It splits a research problem into atomic specialist prompts,
  dispatches each where it runs best across Claude, ChatGPT, Gemini, and
  Perplexity, and converges their outputs into a single living document called
  the Master. v2 introduces the PRISM Lens Library — a reference catalog of
  audit-scope lenses graded against the draft Prompt Strategy at Setup to
  surface silent omissions before any prompt ships. v2.1 adds machine-readable
  frontmatter, a strength × polarity normativity vocabulary, and an
  observation-driven appendix indexing vendor parsing behaviour on dispatched
  content. v2.4 generalizes the reserved execution-mode flag into three
  orthogonal orchestration axes — surface, execution driver, and persistence —
  each a closed validated enum; v2.5 lands the repo-backed persistence
  mechanics, holding durable state in a GitHub repo with the running
  What's-next artifact made repo-resident as the cross-surface pickup point.
  v2.6 adds corpus-access dispatch (Phase 1): a first-class investigation
  posture for retrieving from named sources and document corpora, kept
  structurally distinct from epistemic triangulation, with a coverage fan
  that merges returns for recall and a mandatory exhibits manifest carrying
  per-item provenance.
  v2.7 adds recommended-sources-on-lens: an optional Lens Library field
  binding framework-curated external reference sources, each with a
  mandatory framing and recency caveat, to a lens's material question.
  v2.7's consuming behaviour lands in v2.8 as corpus-access Phase 2: a
  lens-anchored auto-trigger that recognizes when a lens's recommended
  source answers the question being worked and proposes a lookup for
  operator ratification rather than auto-dispatching, auto-populating the
  framing and recency caveats so they cannot be silently omitted.
  v2.9 declares the orchestration substrate by vendor and tier (Claude,
  Opus-class) rather than pinned model versions, and decomposes the framework
  into a lean always-loaded core plus on-demand reference bundles, packaged as
  a Claude Skill plugin alongside the canonical single-file form.
  v2.10 adds the Scope-Integrity Test: a coverage-time falsifier gate that
  enforces that a lens's minimum scope binding was actually satisfied, not
  waved through, on a rigor ladder from inline self-check to cross-vendor
  probe, with an optional per-lens sharpened-probe field; the embedded Lens
  Library advances to v0.16.
  v2.11 adds an explicit Skill slash-command invocation path on Claude —
  `/prism-start <subject>` activates PRISM and begins Setup for the supplied
  subject — a Claude-Skill packaging affordance carried by a plugin slash-command,
  alongside the unchanged natural-language invocation that remains the portable
  form on every vendor.
  v2.12 adds a companion `/prism-whats-next` command that resumes an engagement
  from the Master's What's-next artifact.
  v2.13–v2.14 add the output-discipline family — the uninvited-frame rule
  (the Elephant Rule), plain-words / recompute / claims-carry-their-basis /
  editions-stand-alone principles, and an Independent Validation Dispatch.
  v2.15 ("Foundations") adds two Standing Principles — trust-structure /
  self-report-advisory and surface-translation — a retrieved-versus-inferred
  finding-basis axis, filename-authoritative vendor reconciliation, Setup
  stakeholder-positioning, and a Setup-artifact re-audit.
  v2.16 ("Operating-model backbone") adds the lanes / roles operating model —
  every engagement runs as parallel lanes worked by sessions in a role ×
  context-tier matrix — with the PRISM Desk and PRISM Meta standing lanes and
  an operator-facing PRISM UI; an append-only cross-lane open-items inbox with
  commit discipline; bundle-load integrity; Setup onboarding (a Setup-generated
  per-engagement system-instructions file plus a first-class quick mode); and
  M5 self-banding.
  v2.17 ("Dispatch round-trip") names the dispatch round-trip as one bounded
  construct — the five-stage dispatch lifecycle (build, dispatch, execute,
  return/converge, reconcile) — with a late-bound build that requires a pass
  spec rather than a frozen envelope, a proactive return-handling card and a
  failure leg routed by type, a unique dispatch identifier paired with the
  copy-through digest so a return reconciles to the exact dispatch instance, a
  fanned Independent-Validation adjudicate-by-re-derivation refinement, and
  passive pre-fill of self-report.
  v2.18 ("Lifecycle & deliverables") adds a symmetric engagement-closure gate — a
  three-layer close sweep bookending three-layer readiness, with an orphan-sweep,
  a reconcile-at-close codification sweep, and deliverable polish — and codifies
  the engagement deliverable: a comprehensive verdict-first final report, an
  optional interactive workbook, a presentation house-style, deliverable
  bump-atomicity (shipped equals validated), and an external-share family (one
  repo per engagement, a de-coded share archive, and an image-redaction
  procedure).
  v2.19 ("Core-slimming refactor") slims the always-loaded core by projecting
  its phase-, seam-, and condition-scoped mechanics — Setup, currency
  maintenance, session continuity and recovery, and corpus-access — into four
  on-demand reference bundles keyed to the role that needs them, each reachable
  through an in-core trigger stub and the phase → bundle manifest; the canonical
  single-file form is unchanged.
  v2.20 re-embeds the Lens Library at v0.16 — adding the reader-respect lens
  "Does this respect the reader?", which flags filler that wastes the reader's
  time and completes the document-review family, and curating external
  recommended-sources on the comparison and unit-economics lenses — and names
  that lens in the Independent Validation Dispatch default kit.
  v2.21 ("External-review hardening") hardens the methodology from external
  review — turn-close evaluate-then-emit ordering, a Self-check
  visible-recompute line and a first-token Dispatch-ID echo, a clean split
  between the orchestration dispatch record and the self-contained execution
  seat paste, and a heavy-line-versus-XML dispatch-delimiter rationale — and
  adds a runtime front door: a /prism-help orientation command and an
  orientation-before-engagement core behavior.
  The framework codifies a triple execution contract
  (Envelope · Self-check · Output), Monitors, Standing Principles, a telemetric
  context-pressure framework, and continuous Master + What's-next state —
  distributed as a single markdown file that can be attached to any LLM session
  or installed as a Claude Skill.
